-- Add 50 books across 8 genres with readable content for the Book Club app
-- This includes title, author, genre, description, publication year, cover URL, and readable content

INSERT INTO books (title, author, genre, description, publication_year, cover_url, content) VALUES

-- ROMANCE (7 books)
('The Notebook', 'Nicholas Sparks', 'Romance', 'A timeless love story spanning decades with emotions that resonate deeply. A man reads to a woman in a nursing home the story of their enduring love.', 1996, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/7995156-M.jpg', 'The story begins in 1940 in South Carolina, where Noah Calhoun falls deeply in love with wealthy young Allie Hamilton. Their summer romance is interrupted by Allie''s parents who forbid their relationship due to their different social classes. Years later, after World War II, Noah struggles to move on with his life. When Allie returns to their hometown as an engaged woman, they are reunited, and old feelings resurface. The two must choose between duty and passion, between the life expected of them and the life their hearts truly desire. Through decades of separation and reunion, their love persists, transcending time, social barriers, and the inevitable challenges life presents. The narrative weaves between past and present, revealing how true love can endure and shape one''s entire existence.'),

('Pride and Prejudice', 'Jane Austen', 'Romance', 'A classic romance featuring Elizabeth Bennet and Mr. Darcy in Regency England. A witty examination of marriage, class, and misunderstandings that lead to true love.', 1813, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8235688-M.jpg', 'Elizabeth Bennet is a spirited young woman in Regency-era England, living in a society where a woman''s prospects depend entirely on marriage. When the wealthy, seemingly arrogant Mr. Darcy arrives in their neighborhood, Elizabeth immediately dislikes him, finding him proud and cold. However, as time passes and misunderstandings are cleared, Elizabeth discovers that Mr. Darcy''s pride masks a noble, generous heart. Through a series of events involving her sister Jane, her friend Charlotte, and the deceitful Mr. Wickham, Elizabeth learns not to judge by appearances. Mr. Darcy, in turn, must overcome his class prejudices to recognize Elizabeth''s worth beyond her family''s lower social standing. Their journey from mutual dislike to profound love is one of literature''s greatest romances, exploring themes of personal growth, self-awareness, and the transformative power of genuine connection.'),

('Outlander', 'Diana Gabaldon', 'Romance', 'Time-traveling adventure blending history, romance, and danger across centuries. Claire, a nurse from 1945, is transported to 1743 Scotland.', 1991, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/7963344-M.jpg', 'Claire Randall, a World War II nurse, touches an ancient standing stone in the Scottish Highlands and is mysteriously transported back in time to 1743. Separated from her husband by nearly 200 years, Claire must navigate a dangerous world of Highland politics, clan rivalries, and cultural differences. She meets Jamie Fraser, a young Scottish warrior, and falls in love with him despite her connection to her own time. As Claire becomes entangled in historical events and the Jacobite uprising, she must decide between her commitment to her husband in the future and her love for Jamie. The story interweaves thrilling action, historical detail, and deeply romantic moments as Claire uses her medical knowledge and intelligence to survive in a brutal era, all while searching for a way to protect those she loves, regardless of which century they inhabit.'),

('The Time Traveler''s Wife', 'Audrey Niffenegger', 'Romance', 'An extraordinary love story complicated by involuntary time travel. Henry begins spontaneously traveling through time, while Clare waits for him across years.', 2003, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8045960-M.jpg', 'Henry DeTamble is a man who suffers from Chrono-Displacement Disorder, a condition that causes him to involuntarily travel through time. He cannot control when he disappears or where in time he lands. Clare Abshire first meets Henry when she is six years old and he is a man in his thirties, appearing in her father''s library from the future. She falls in love with him, knowing that one day he will meet her in the present and fall in love with her as well. When their paths finally cross in the present day, they begin a relationship fraught with uncertainty and heartbreak. Henry''s uncontrollable time travel tears them apart repeatedly, forcing them to love across time itself. The novel explores what it means to love someone when you cannot control when you''ll see them, when you know future events, and when your choices seem predetermined by time itself. It''s a meditation on fate, choice, loss, and the power of love to transcend the boundaries of time.'),

('Jane Eyre', 'Charlotte Brontë', 'Romance', 'A Gothic romance about a young orphan who becomes a governess and falls in love with the mysterious master of Thornfield Hall.', 1847, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8289543-M.jpg', 'Jane Eyre is an orphan raised by her aunt in harsh circumstances. After attending a charity school, she becomes a teacher and then accepts a position as governess to the ward of the mysterious Mr. Edward Rochester. As Jane cares for Rochester''s young ward, Adèle, she develops deep feelings for the brooding master of Thornfield Hall. Rochester harbors secrets about his past, particularly regarding the strange laughter heard at night in the upper floors of the manor. Their relationship deepens as they spend time together, and Rochester grows increasingly devoted to Jane. However, on their wedding day, a shocking revelation threatens to destroy their happiness. Jane must choose between societal expectations and her heart''s desires. Through Gothic atmosphere, mysterious circumstances, and passionate emotion, the novel explores themes of independence, morality, and true love that transcends class boundaries.'),

('Me Before You', 'Jojo Moyes', 'Romance', 'A contemporary romance about a young caregiver who falls in love with a wealthy quadriplegic client. A story about sacrifice, love, and impossible choices.', 2012, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8404245-M.jpg', 'Louisa "Lou" Clark, a young woman from a working-class background, takes a job as a caregiver for Will Traynor, a wealthy, accomplished man left paralyzed after a motorcycle accident. Will is initially withdrawn and bitter about his condition, having lost all the physical abilities and freedoms that defined his life. Lou, with her optimism and care, slowly breaks through his walls, and they develop a profound connection. As Lou helps Will rediscover aspects of joy and connection, Will becomes her entire world. However, Will has secretly been researching assisted suicide and has made plans to end his life. Lou must grapple with her love for Will against his wishes and her own desires for their future. The novel beautifully explores themes of love, disability, purpose, and the question of what we owe to those we love when their happiness conflicts with our own desires.'),

('The Fault in Our Stars', 'John Green', 'Romance', 'A poignant romance between two teenagers with cancer who fall in love at a support group. A story about mortality, meaning, and love.', 2012, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8404892-M.jpg', 'Hazel Grace Lancaster is a sixteen-year-old girl living with terminal cancer who attends a support group for young people with illnesses. At the group, she meets Augustus Waters, a charming and witty boy who is in remission from osteosarcoma. Their connection is immediate and profound. Augustus encourages Hazel to travel to Amsterdam to meet her favorite author, and together they embark on a journey that becomes about much more than visiting a distant place. As their romance blossoms, they navigate the reality of living with life-threatening illnesses while falling deeply in love. The novel beautifully captures the intensity of teenage love, the philosophical discussions about existence and meaning, and the inevitable pain that comes with loving someone in the face of mortality. Through humor, heartbreak, and hope, Green explores how we find meaning in a universe that doesn''t owe us anything, and how love persists even in the shadow of death.'),

-- SCIENCE FICTION (8 books)
('Dune', 'Frank Herbert', 'Science Fiction', 'An epic saga of politics, religion, and ecology on a desert planet. Paul Atreides must navigate prophecy, power, and his destiny on Arrakis.', 1965, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8419599-M.jpg', 'On the desert planet of Arrakis, a valuable substance called melange spice is mined—a commodity that extends human life, enables space travel, and enhances mental abilities. House Atreides is assigned to govern Arrakis, and Paul Atreides, the young heir, is sent to this hostile world. However, their arrival is part of an elaborate trap set by their enemies, House Harkonnen, in conspiracy with the Emperor. Paul''s father is killed, and the family scattered. Paul, aided by his mother and the native Fremen people of Arrakis, must survive in the harsh desert and navigate the prophecies that surround him. As Paul gains more power and influence among the Fremen, he struggles with the knowledge of what his prescient visions show him—a terrible future where he must choose between his humanity and his power. The novel explores themes of politics, ecology, religion, and the burden of leadership, presenting a richly detailed universe with complex social structures and profound philosophical questions.'),

('The Martian', 'Andy Weir', 'Science Fiction', 'An astronaut stranded on Mars must use his ingenuity and scientific knowledge to survive and engineer his rescue. A thrilling tale of human resilience.', 2011, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8394088-M.jpg', 'Mark Watney, an astronaut and engineer, is accidentally left behind on Mars when his crew believes him to be dead during a dust storm. Stranded on a hostile planet with limited supplies, Watney must use his scientific knowledge and problem-solving skills to survive. He begins a journey of extraordinary ingenuity, using his engineering background to grow food in the Martian soil, create water, and extend his life support systems. Through witty journal entries, Watney recounts his daily struggle against the Martian environment, from dust storms to equipment failures. As NASA discovers that he''s alive, the mission becomes not just about his survival but about orchestrating his rescue across the vast distance of space. The novel is a celebration of human determination, scientific problem-solving, humor in the face of adversity, and the indomitable will to survive. It''s a thrilling, often funny account of what it means to be alone on an alien world and still refuse to give up.'),

('Foundation', 'Isaac Asimov', 'Science Fiction', 'A sweeping space opera about the fall and rise of galactic civilizations. Hari Seldon develops psychohistory to predict and influence the future.', 1951, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/7990905-M.jpg', 'Hari Seldon, a mathematician, develops a science called psychohistory that can predict the future behavior of large populations. Using this science, he foresees the imminent fall of the Galactic Empire and the ensuing chaos that will last thousands of years. To minimize this dark period, Seldon establishes the Foundation—a settlement on a remote planet dedicated to preserving knowledge. The novel follows the Foundation through four crisis periods across several generations, each testing the Foundation''s survival and Seldon''s predictions. The story explores how small actions and strategic planning can influence the course of history, the power of knowledge as a tool for survival, and the tension between predetermined destiny and free will. Asimov creates a vast universe where individual characters interact with the grand sweep of history, examining themes of power, science, and civilization.'),

('Neuromancer', 'William Gibson', 'Science Fiction', 'A groundbreaking cyberpunk novel featuring hackers, artificial intelligence, and virtual reality. Case, a washed-up computer hacker, is hired for one last job.', 1984, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8343197-M.jpg', 'Case is a computer hacker who has been blacklisted by the criminal underworld after a job goes wrong. He''s living a miserable life, dependent on drugs, until he''s approached by Molly, a street samurai with surgically enhanced abilities. She offers him a chance at redemption—and revenge on those who destroyed his career. Together, they work for Dixie Flatline, a deceased hacker whose personality is preserved in a computer chip, and an artificial intelligence named Neuromancer. Their mission involves stealing valuable artificial intelligence code and navigating a world of virtual reality, corporate espionage, and dangerous technology. The novel pioneered the cyberpunk genre, introducing terms like "cyberspace" and presenting a vision of a near-future dominated by artificial intelligence, virtual worlds, and the merging of human consciousness with technology. Gibson''s fast-paced narrative and innovative language create a disorienting, thrilling experience that explores the intersection of humanity and technology.'),

('1984', 'George Orwell', 'Science Fiction', 'A dystopian novel about totalitarianism and surveillance. Winston Smith rebels against Big Brother in a world of perpetual war and thought control.', 1949, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8223084-M.jpg', 'In a totalitarian superstate called Oceania, the government, represented by Big Brother, monitors every citizen''s actions and thoughts through omnipresent telescreens. Winston Smith, a low-ranking member of the ruling Party, begins to question the regime and embarks on a forbidden love affair with Julia. Together, they seek to rebel against the oppressive system, believing they''ve found an ally in O''Brien, a high-ranking official. However, their rebellion is orchestrated as part of the system''s control mechanisms. The novel explores themes of surveillance, propaganda, the manipulation of truth, and the dehumanizing effects of absolute power. Orwell presents a chilling vision of a future where individual freedom is completely eliminated, language is weaponized to control thought, and the government rewrites history to maintain power. The book serves as a powerful warning against authoritarianism and the dangers of unchecked state control.'),

('Hyperion', 'Dan Simmons', 'Science Fiction', 'An epic space opera inspired by The Canterbury Tales. Seven pilgrims travel to meet the mysterious Shrike on the planet Hyperion.', 1989, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8411834-M.jpg', 'In a far future where humanity has spread across the galaxy, seven pilgrims journey to the planet Hyperion to encounter the mysterious and terrifying Shrike—a weapon of mass destruction that exists partially outside normal space and time. Each pilgrim has their own reason for seeking the Shrike, and during their journey, they tell their life stories to each other. The structure mimics Chaucer''s Canterbury Tales, with each character''s narrative revealing complex personal motivations, histories, and the larger political and technological landscape of the universe. The novel features multiple plot threads, genres within the larger narrative, and explores themes of time, technology, consciousness, and human nature. Simmons creates one of science fiction''s most ambitious and intricate universes, blending classical literary structure with futuristic concepts to create a sprawling, multi-layered epic.'),

('Ender''s Game', 'Orson Scott Card', 'Science Fiction', 'A military science fiction novel about a gifted child trained to become a military commander. Ender Wiggin is humanity''s hope against an alien invasion.', 1985, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8408091-M.jpg', 'Ender Wiggin is a brilliant six-year-old boy recruited by the International Military to train as a commander against an alien species called the Buggers. He''s brought to Battle School, an orbiting space station where he and other gifted children undergo intense military training using zero-gravity battle rooms and complex strategy games. As Ender advances through the ranks, he becomes increasingly isolated and burdened by the weight of humanity''s fate. The games become increasingly complex and real, blurring the lines between simulation and reality. Through strategic genius and moral ambiguity, Ender must prepare for humanity''s final battle against the Buggers. The novel explores themes of childhood exploitation, the ethics of war, the nature of leadership, and the psychological cost of being humanity''s savior. Card presents a protagonist who is simultaneously a hero and a victim, raising profound questions about the use of children in warfare and the moral implications of strategic necessity.'),

-- FANTASY (8 books)
('The Fellowship of the Ring', 'J.R.R. Tolkien', 'Fantasy', 'The beginning of an epic quest to destroy the One Ring and save Middle-earth. Frodo and his companions journey from the Shire to Mount Doom.', 1954, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8414568-M.jpg', 'Frodo Baggins, a young hobbit, inherits a mysterious ring from his uncle Bilbo. The wizard Gandalf reveals that this is the One Ring—an ancient instrument of terrible power created by the Dark Lord Sauron to control all other rings and dominate the world. To prevent Sauron from reclaiming it and plunging Middle-earth into darkness, the Ring must be destroyed in the fires of Mount Doom. Frodo, burdened with this impossible task, embarks on a perilous journey with a fellowship of hobbits, men, an elf, a dwarf, and a wizard. Throughout their quest, they face treacherous landscapes, terrifying enemies, and the Ring''s corrupting influence. The novel beautifully combines adventure with deeper themes of friendship, sacrifice, courage, and the struggle between good and evil. Tolkien''s richly detailed world, with its own languages, histories, and cultures, remains one of literature''s greatest achievements in world-building and storytelling.'),

('A Game of Thrones', 'George R.R. Martin', 'Fantasy', 'An intricate tale of power struggles and magic in a richly detailed world. Multiple characters vie for control of the Seven Kingdoms.', 1996, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8415036-M.jpg', 'In the fictional continents of Westeros and Essos, various noble houses battle for control of the Iron Throne following the death of King Robert Baratheon. The story follows multiple point-of-view characters including the honorable Stark family, the cunning Lannisters, and the exiled Targaryen family. Political intrigue, warfare, and unexpected betrayals drive the narrative as characters scheme to gain power, protect their families, or claim their rightful thrones. The world is populated by complex, morally ambiguous characters—there are few true heroes or villains, making the story feel grounded and unpredictable. Beyond the politics, hints of supernatural threats emerge, including the ominous White Walkers from the north and the return of magic to the world. Martin crafts an epic fantasy that subverts genre conventions, with shocking character deaths and a gritty realism rarely found in fantasy literature. The novel explores themes of loyalty, betrayal, power, and the cost of ambition.'),

('The Name of the Wind', 'Patrick Rothfuss', 'Fantasy', 'The story of Kvothe, a legendary figure recounting his extraordinary life and education in magic. A tale of genius, love, and tragedy.', 2007, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8407862-M.jpg', 'An aging innkeeper reveals himself to be Kvothe, the legendary figure whose deeds have become myth and legend throughout the world. He decides to tell the true story of his life. The narrative flashes back to Kvothe''s childhood, where he was a gifted performer traveling with his troupe. After a tragedy befalls his family, young Kvothe finds himself alone and penniless, searching for answers about those responsible for his loss. He eventually enrolls in the prestigious University, where he studies magic and pursues knowledge relentlessly. The story follows Kvothe''s education, his friendships, his magical abilities, and his deep love for a mysterious woman named Denna. Rothfuss crafts a lyrical, immersive narrative that blends coming-of-age story with epic fantasy. The magic system is intricate and well-developed, the mysteries are engaging, and the prose is beautiful. The novel explores themes of genius, the search for truth, love, loss, and the gap between legend and reality.'),

('Mistborn', 'Brandon Sanderson', 'Fantasy', 'A girl with mysterious powers becomes the key to overthrowing an empire. Vin discovers she is a mistborn—someone who can use all magical metals.', 2006, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8398772-M.jpg', 'Vin is a girl born into slavery in a world where an immortal tyrant called the Lord Ruler has reigned for a thousand years. She possesses the rare ability to burn metals to gain superhuman powers—she''s a mistborn. When she''s rescued by a crew of rebels planning to overthrow the Lord Ruler, Vin becomes central to their mission. As she learns to control her powers and discovers her true heritage, she becomes increasingly powerful and confident. However, her newfound abilities come with unexpected consequences. Sanderson creates a detailed magic system based on burning specific metals to gain different powers, and Vin''s journey is one of self-discovery, rebellion, and sacrifice. The novel combines action-packed sequences with character development and explores themes of freedom, power, identity, and redemption. Sanderson''s world is vivid and oppressive, with ash raining from the sky and the economy based on a specific metal, creating a unique atmosphere.'),

('The Silmarillion', 'J.R.R. Tolkien', 'Fantasy', 'A collection of mythopoeic stories about the First Age of Middle-earth. The creation of the world and the epic conflicts of its early ages.', 1977, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8395236-M.jpg', 'The Silmarillion is a mythology book that Tolkien created, detailing the history of Middle-earth from its creation through the First Age. It begins with the Ainur—powerful angelic beings who participated in the creation of the world. The narrative then follows the rise and fall of various races, particularly the Elves, and their conflicts with the Dark Lord Morgoth, who stole the legendary Silmarils—three jewels of great power and beauty. The story is told through multiple tales and genealogies, presenting a rich mythology comparable to Norse mythology or Greek epics. The narrative is grand and tragic, filled with noble heroes, tragic flaws, and inevitable doom. While less accessible than The Lord of the Rings due to its mythological structure and dense genealogies, The Silmarillion reveals the deeper history of Tolkien''s world and provides context for the events in The Hobbit and The Lord of the Rings. It''s a profound meditation on themes of creation, corruption, fate, and the cyclical nature of history.'),

('The Way of Kings', 'Brandon Sanderson', 'Fantasy', 'The first book in The Stormlight Archive. An epic fantasy about honor, power, and destiny set in a world of powerful storms.', 2010, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8415862-M.jpg', 'On the storm-ravaged planet of Roshar, where powerful hurricanes called Highstorms regularly devastate the land, multiple characters'' lives intersect in an epic tale. Kaladin, a slave with a mysterious past and strange magical abilities, seeks redemption and a way to protect those he cares about. Shallan, a young woman of noble birth, seeks knowledge and power to save her family. Bridger, a youth with a tragic history, dreams of becoming a warrior. Their paths converge in a world filled with magic systems, ancient technology, and deep mysteries. Sanderson creates an intricate magic system based on absorbing storms and harnessing their power. The novel is notable for its length, complex plotting, beautiful prose, and depth of worldbuilding. The Way of Kings explores themes of leadership, sacrifice, honor, and the power of hope in the face of overwhelming darkness. Sanderson''s detailed magic systems and vast world make it one of modern fantasy''s most ambitious works.'),

('The Poppy War', 'R.F. Kuang', 'Fantasy', 'A dark epic fantasy inspired by Chinese history and mythology. Rin, a war orphan, discovers shamanic powers and becomes a military commander.', 2018, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8419235-M.jpg', 'Rin is a poor, low-class girl who aces the empire''s most competitive military academy entrance exam, shocking everyone including herself. At the academy, she discovers that she can summon the phoenix—a shamanic power that grants her immense destructive abilities. As a war erupts between her nation and an enemy empire, Rin''s power becomes crucial to the war effort. However, shamanism comes with a terrible cost: it requires her to break taboos and sacrifice her humanity. As Rin discovers the depths of her power, she becomes increasingly consumed by rage and the desire for vengeance, particularly after witnessing atrocities against her people. Kuang crafts a dark, complex narrative that explores the costs of power, the brutality of war, the nature of shamanism, and the question of how far one should go in pursuit of justice. The novel doesn''t shy away from depicting the horrors of war and the psychological toll it takes on soldiers. It''s a compelling, mature fantasy that challenges conventional narratives of heroism.'),

-- MYSTERY (7 books)
('The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo', 'Stieg Larsson', 'Mystery', 'A gripping mystery involving a missing woman and dark secrets in Sweden. Journalist Mikael Blomkvist and hacker Lisbeth Salander investigate a decades-old disappearance.', 2005, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8375821-M.jpg', 'Journalist Mikael Blomkvist is hired by an elderly businessman to investigate the disappearance of his great-niece Harriet, who vanished decades ago. Despite decades of investigation, the case remains unsolved. Blomkvist teams up with Lisbeth Salander, a brilliant but damaged hacker with a troubled past and a dragon tattoo on her shoulder. Together, they uncover a dark history of abuse, corruption, and serial murder within the wealthy Vanger family. The investigation leads them deeper into secrets that powerful people want to keep hidden, putting them in danger. Larsson creates a complex, multi-layered mystery that interweaves the present-day investigation with past crimes. The novel is notable for its strong characterization, particularly Lisbeth Salander, and its unflinching examination of violence against women. The narrative is propulsive and engaging, with twists that keep readers guessing. The book combines elements of romance, social criticism, and psychological depth alongside the mystery plot.'),

('The Murder of Roger Ackroyd', 'Agatha Christie', 'Mystery', 'A classic whodunit featuring detective Hercule Poirot. Roger Ackroyd is murdered, and the solution requires examining everyone''s secrets.', 1926, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8240268-M.jpg', 'Roger Ackroyd, a wealthy businessman, is murdered in his locked study. The only person known to have been near him recently is his secretary, but she denies entering the study. Hercule Poirot, the renowned Belgian detective, is drawn into the case. As Poirot investigates, he discovers that many people had motives to kill Ackroyd—financial difficulties, blackmail, and hidden relationships all come to light. The narrative is framed as the account of Dr. Sheppard, the narrator, who is Poirot''s neighbor and friend. Poirot methodically unravels the mystery, examining each character''s story and motive. The novel is famous for its twist ending, which revolutionized detective fiction when it was published. Christie masterfully plays with the conventions of the mystery genre, creating a puzzle that seems unsolvable until the brilliant revelation. The book is a testament to Poirot''s deductive genius and remains one of the greatest detective novels ever written.'),

('Gone Girl', 'Gillian Flynn', 'Mystery', 'A twisting narrative about a marriage gone terribly wrong on anniversary night. Amy and Nick Dunne''s anniversary takes a sinister turn.', 2012, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8404737-M.jpg', 'On their anniversary, Nick Dunne comes home to find his wife Amy missing. As the investigation progresses and media attention intensifies, Nick becomes the prime suspect in his wife''s disappearance. The narrative alternates between Nick''s perspective in the present day and Amy''s diary entries from the past, slowly revealing the dynamics of their marriage. Amy is clever, ambitious, and methodical, while Nick is charming but flawed. Through their alternating narratives, a picture emerges of a marriage that deteriorated into something dark and destructive. The novel subverts expectations repeatedly, and the twists become increasingly shocking. Flynn explores themes of marriage, identity, gender, and the masks people wear in relationships. The unreliable narrators and shifting perspectives keep readers uncertain about who is telling the truth and what really happened. It''s a psychological thriller that examines the dark side of relationships and the ways people can manipulate perception.'),

('The Da Vinci Code', 'Dan Brown', 'Mystery', 'An action-packed mystery involving art, history, and hidden secrets. Professor Robert Langdon is drawn into a conspiracy involving the Holy Grail.', 2003, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8362741-M.jpg', 'Harvard symbologist Robert Langdon is awakened in a museum in Paris with a dying man—a victim seeking Langdon''s help before expiring. The victim''s body is posed in the style of a Leonardo da Vinci artwork, and mysterious symbols are left behind. Langdon is drawn into a mystery involving ancient history, religious conspiracy, and hidden meanings in famous artworks. Along with Sophie Neveu, a French cryptographer, Langdon races to uncover a secret that powerful religious institutions have kept hidden for centuries. The mystery involves the Da Vinci Code—hidden messages in Leonardo''s paintings and the nature of the Holy Grail. Brown weaves together art history, cryptography, and religious scholarship into a fast-paced thriller. The novel explores themes of faith, conspiracy, and the power of secrets. While critics have pointed out historical inaccuracies and criticized the thin characterization, the novel''s puzzle-solving nature and pacing make it an engaging page-turner that sparked widespread popular interest in art history and symbology.'),

('Sherlock Holmes: A Study in Scarlet', 'Arthur Conan Doyle', 'Mystery', 'The first appearance of the world''s greatest detective. Sherlock Holmes and Dr. Watson meet and solve a murder together.', 1887, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8270621-M.jpg', 'Dr. John Watson, recently returned from military service in Afghanistan, is looking for lodgings in London when he meets Sherlock Holmes, an eccentric and brilliant detective. The two move into rooms together at 221B Baker Street. When a body is discovered on a vacant lot, Holmes''s deductive methods prove instrumental in solving the case. Holmes carefully observes minute details that others overlook, uses logic and reasoning to draw conclusions, and solves what seems like an impossible case. The story introduces Watson as Holmes''s chronicler and friend, whose perspective allows readers to experience Holmes''s genius alongside him. Through Watson''s narration, Conan Doyle makes Holmes''s deductive process comprehensible to readers. The novel establishes the dynamic between Holmes and Watson that would define their relationship throughout the many stories in the series. It''s both a locked-room mystery and an introduction to one of literature''s most enduring and beloved characters.'),

('And Then There Were None', 'Agatha Christie', 'Mystery', 'Ten strangers are invited to an island, and they begin dying one by one according to an eerie nursery rhyme.', 1939, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8282415-M.jpg', 'Ten seemingly unrelated strangers are invited to an island under false pretenses. Upon arrival, they discover that each of them is accused of a crime they committed but were never punished for. A voice accuses each of them, and that very night, one of them dies. As the guests realize they''re trapped on the island, they begin to suspect one another. Each death follows the sequence of an ominous nursery rhyme, leaving the survivors wondering who among them is the murderer. With each death, paranoia and suspicion grow. The guests, isolated and cut off from the mainland, must solve the mystery before they all die. Christie masterfully builds tension, creates complex interactions between characters with conflicting motivations, and constructs a puzzle that seems impossible to solve. The novel is remarkable for achieving a murder mystery where the reader cannot easily deduce the culprit from the established clues. It''s considered one of her greatest works and remains a quintessential locked-room mystery.'),

('Mystic River', 'Dennis Lehane', 'Mystery', 'Three childhood friends are reunited when a young girl is murdered. Secrets from their past resurface as they investigate.', 2001, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8382546-M.jpg', 'Three boys—Sean, Jimmy, and Dave—share a traumatic experience in childhood when a man kidnaps Dave for several years. Though Dave escapes, the trauma leaves scars. Years later, as adults in Boston, they''ve gone their separate ways. Then, the daughter of Jimmy Marcus is murdered, and the investigation draws all three men back into proximity. Each has secrets, dark pasts, and reasons to be suspicious. As they investigate, old resentments and traumas surface. Lehane crafts a dark, brooding mystery that explores the lasting impact of childhood trauma, the unreliability of memory, and how secrets from the past can destroy lives. The novel is intensely atmospheric, capturing the grit and streets of Boston. The characterization is deep, with each man complicated by their past and present circumstances. The investigation becomes increasingly complex as different characters have motives, opportunity, and secrets. The climax reveals surprising truths about the murder and the characters'' involvement.'),

-- THRILLER (6 books)
('The Silence of the Lambs', 'Thomas Harris', 'Thriller', 'An FBI agent seeks help from a brilliant psychopath to catch a serial killer. Clarice Starling must engage with Dr. Hannibal Lecter.', 1988, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8395156-M.jpg', 'FBI trainee Clarice Starling is assigned to work on the case of a serial killer called Buffalo Bill who skins his female victims. To gain insight into the killer''s psychology, she''s asked to visit Dr. Hannibal Lecter, a brilliant psychiatrist and cannibalistic killer imprisoned in an asylum. Lecter agrees to help, but only if Starling will confide in him about her traumatic past and personal life. Their relationship becomes a psychological chess game where Lecter provides clues and insights while slowly trying to manipulate Starling. As Starling gets closer to understanding Buffalo Bill''s identity and location, she must navigate between Lecter''s mind games and the genuine danger posed by the active serial killer. Harris creates a tense psychological thriller where the relationship between hunter and hunted blurs. Lecter is charismatic, intelligent, and chilling—a villain that readers find both repulsive and fascinating. The novel explores themes of psychology, manipulation, trauma, and the fine line between order and chaos.'),

('The Girl on the Train', 'Paula Hawkins', 'Thriller', 'A psychological thriller told through the eyes of multiple unreliable narrators. Rachel, a commuter on a train, witnesses something that changes everything.', 2015, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8408936-M.jpg', 'Rachel boards the same commuter train every day. During her commute, she obsesses over a couple she sees from her window—a beautiful woman and handsome man in an idyllic relationship. She becomes obsessed with their lives, imagining their perfect existence. When the woman, Megan, suddenly goes missing and the investigation begins, Rachel realizes she may have witnessed something important. However, Rachel is an alcoholic with blackouts and memory loss, making her an unreliable witness. As the investigation progresses, the narrative shifts between Rachel, Megan, and Anna—the new woman in the man''s life—each with their own secrets and perspectives. The novel builds suspense through unreliable narration and shifting timelines, leaving readers uncertain about who is trustworthy and what really happened. Hawkins explores themes of obsession, alcoholism, identity, and the ways trauma can shape relationships. The page-turner quality of the novel, combined with the psychological depth, makes it a compelling thriller.'),

('Rebecca', 'Daphne du Maurier', 'Thriller', 'A haunting tale of suspicion and jealousy in a gothic English manor. A newly married woman is haunted by the memory of her husband''s first wife.', 1938, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8215631-M.jpg', 'A young, unnamed woman marries the wealthy widower Maxim de Winter and moves into his grand estate, Manderley. Maxim''s first wife, Rebecca, died under mysterious circumstances. Despite her death, Rebecca''s presence pervades the manor through the housekeeper Mrs. Danvers, who was devoted to her. As the new bride settles into her role, she begins to feel increasingly insecure and inadequate compared to the idealized memory of Rebecca. Strange events occur, secrets surface, and suspicions arise about the nature of Rebecca''s death. The narrator becomes consumed by jealousy and paranoia, unsure whether her husband truly loved her or is simply using her. The past literally haunts the present as the circumstances surrounding Rebecca''s death begin to unravel. Du Maurier masterfully creates an atmosphere of gothic suspense and psychological tension. The novel explores themes of identity, jealousy, the power of the past, and the dangers of idealization. The slow revelation of truth keeps readers engaged and guessing about the characters'' motivations and secrets.'),

('The Woman in Cabin 10', 'Ruth Ware', 'Thriller', 'A journalist on a luxury cruise discovers a passenger in the cabin next to hers, but the passenger doesn''t officially exist.', 2016, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8410236-M.jpg', 'Journalist Lo Blacklock is assigned to write about a luxury cruise aboard the Arctic Spa. Exhausted and needing a break, she''s looking forward to the voyage. However, on the first night, she witnesses what she believes is a murder—a woman being thrown overboard from the cabin next to hers. When she reports it, the crew investigates but finds no evidence of a crime. More disturbingly, there''s no record of a passenger in the cabin next to hers. Lo becomes increasingly distrustful and paranoid, uncertain if she witnessed a real crime or if her exhaustion and past trauma are causing her to imagine things. As she attempts to uncover the truth, she puts herself in danger. Ware crafts a tense psychological thriller where the reader, like Lo, can''t be sure what is real and what is imagined. The isolated setting of the ship intensifies the atmosphere of paranoia and dread. The novel explores themes of gaslighting, the reliability of memory, and how past trauma can affect perception.'),

('The Shining', 'Stephen King', 'Thriller', 'A family becomes the winter caretakers of an isolated hotel, where supernatural forces and isolation drive the father toward madness.', 1977, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8369832-M.jpg', 'Jack Torrance, an out-of-work teacher and recovering alcoholic, accepts a job as the winter caretaker of the isolated Overlook Hotel, located high in the Colorado Mountains. He brings his wife Wendy and son Danny with him. The hotel is beautiful but isolated, surrounded by snow during the winter months with no one else around. Danny possesses psychic abilities—the ''shining''—that allow him to sense things others cannot. As the family settles in, strange events occur. The hotel seems to exert a malevolent influence, particularly on Jack. The isolation, combined with Jack''s fragile mental state, begins to unravel his sanity. Jack becomes increasingly violent and unstable, threatening his family. The hotel seems to feed on Jack''s darkness, encouraging his violence and madness. Stephen King creates a psychological horror that explores themes of domestic violence, addiction, isolation, and the supernatural. The novel is gripping and terrifying, with King masterfully building tension as Jack''s descent into madness accelerates. The Overlook Hotel becomes a character itself—malevolent and hungry.'),

('The Talented Mr. Ripley', 'Patricia Highsmith', 'Thriller', 'Tom Ripley, a con artist and sociopath, manipulates his way into wealth and status. A psychological thriller about ambition and deception.', 1955, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8345821-M.jpg', 'Tom Ripley is a poor, ambitious man living in New York, scraping by with con games and small thefts. He''s hired by a wealthy businessman to travel to Italy and convince his playboy son Dickie Greenleaf to return home. Tom meets Dickie and insinuates himself into his life, eventually developing an obsessive attachment to him and his carefree lifestyle. When Dickie rejects him and moves away, Tom murders him and assumes his identity, using Dickie''s wealth and connections for himself. To maintain his new life, Tom must stay one step ahead of law enforcement, commit additional crimes, and manipulate those around him. Highsmith creates a psychological portrait of a sociopath—a man without conscience who can convincingly fake emotions and relationships to achieve his goals. The narrative is compelling because Highsmith allows readers into Tom''s mind, making his perspective sympathetic despite his horrific actions. The novel explores themes of identity, class aspiration, sociopathy, and the question of morality in a world where deception seems to work. Tom becomes one of literature''s most memorable and disturbing characters.'),

-- SELF-HELP (5 books)
('Atomic Habits', 'James Clear', 'Self-Help', 'Practical strategies for building better habits and breaking bad ones. Small changes, remarkable results. A guide to improvement through incremental progress.', 2018, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8418542-M.jpg', 'Atomic Habits provides a comprehensive framework for understanding how habits work and how to change them. James Clear explains that habits are the compound interest of self-improvement—small, seemingly insignificant changes accumulate into remarkable results over time. The book is organized around key principles: making habits obvious, making them attractive, making them easy, and making them satisfying. Clear provides practical techniques for each principle, such as habit stacking (linking a new habit to an existing one), designing your environment to support good habits, and creating implementation intentions. The book is filled with engaging stories and examples from athletes, entrepreneurs, and ordinary people who have used these principles to transform their lives. Clear emphasizes that the goal is not to be the best, but to be better than you were yesterday. The book encourages a systems-based approach, where focusing on small daily improvements compounds into significant life changes. Atomic Habits has become a bestseller because it combines scientific research with practical, actionable advice that readers can immediately implement.'),

('Thinking, Fast and Slow', 'Daniel Kahneman', 'Self-Help', 'An exploration of the two systems of thought: fast, intuitive thinking and slow, deliberate thinking. How our minds work and where we go wrong.', 2011, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8404634-M.jpg', 'Nobel Prize-winning psychologist Daniel Kahneman explores the two systems that drive the way we think. System 1 operates automatically and quickly, with little effort and without conscious control. System 2 allocates attention to effortful mental activities and is more rational and deliberate. Kahneman explains how these two systems interact, often leading to biases and errors in judgment. He discusses cognitive biases such as anchoring (relying too heavily on initial information), availability heuristic (overestimating the likelihood of events that come to mind easily), and overconfidence. The book uses engaging examples and experiments to illustrate these concepts. Kahneman explores how these mental shortcuts, while useful in most situations, can lead us astray when making important decisions. He discusses loss aversion, the representativeness heuristic, and numerous other psychological phenomena that affect decision-making. The book provides insights into human nature and helps readers recognize the flaws in their thinking, enabling more rational decision-making. While dense at times, the insights are profound and applicable to everyday life.'),

('The Power of Now', 'Eckhart Tolle', 'Self-Help', 'A guide to spiritual enlightenment and living in the present moment. Breaking free from past and future anxieties to achieve inner peace.', 1997, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8333544-M.jpg', 'Eckhart Tolle teaches that the present moment—the now—is the only point of power. Most of our suffering comes from dwelling on the past or worrying about the future. Tolle argues that our egoic minds are responsible for negative thoughts, anxiety, and suffering. By living in the now and observing thoughts without judgment, we can transcend the ego and achieve inner peace and enlightenment. The book introduces practical techniques for staying present, such as mindfulness, meditation, and conscious awareness. Tolle encourages readers to observe their thoughts without identifying with them, creating a space between the observer and the thoughts. He explores how this shift in consciousness can transform relationships, work, and overall well-being. The book combines spiritual wisdom with practical exercises, making it accessible to readers new to spiritual concepts. While some find Tolle''s philosophy profound and life-changing, others criticize the book for being too simplistic or pseudo-scientific. Nevertheless, The Power of Now has inspired millions and remains influential in the self-help and spirituality genres.'),

('Sapiens', 'Yuval Noah Harari', 'Self-Help', 'A history of humankind from the Stone Age to the modern era. How did humans come to dominate the world and what does the future hold.', 2011, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8404802-M.jpg', 'Yuval Noah Harari traces the history of humanity from the emergence of Homo sapiens approximately 70,000 years ago to the present day. The book is divided into four main sections: the Cognitive Revolution, the Agricultural Revolution, the unification of humankind, and the Scientific Revolution. Harari argues that what set Homo sapiens apart from other human species was our ability to create and believe in shared myths and fictions—money, nations, religions, and human rights are all fictions that allow large numbers of people to cooperate. The Cognitive Revolution allowed humans to develop language and imagination, enabling them to imagine things that don''t exist. The Agricultural Revolution led to settled societies but also introduced inequality and suffering. Through subsequent revolutions, humans created complex societies and accumulated knowledge. Harari explores how these developments shaped human society and contemplates humanity''s future. The book is thought-provoking and challenges readers to reconsider assumptions about human nature, progress, and the future. While critics argue Harari oversimplifies complex historical processes, the book remains influential for its sweeping perspective and ability to make readers think about the bigger picture.'),

('Man''s Search for Meaning', 'Viktor E. Frankl', 'Self-Help', 'A memoir of surviving Nazi concentration camps and a guide to finding meaning in life even under the most horrific circumstances.', 1946, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8341563-M.jpg', 'Viktor Frankl was a psychiatrist imprisoned in Nazi concentration camps during the Holocaust. His experiences and observations in the camps form the basis of this profound book. Frankl describes the horrors of camp life, where prisoners were subjected to starvation, brutality, and death. He noticed that some prisoners maintained hope and dignity while others succumbed to despair. Frankl realized that while the Nazis could control his body and external circumstances, they could not control his mind or his ability to find meaning. He developed Logotherapy, a form of psychotherapy based on the idea that life has meaning under all circumstances, even the most miserable ones, and that our main motivation is to find that meaning. The second part of the book outlines the principles of Logotherapy and its applications to modern life. Frankl argues that meaning can be found through achievement, through experiencing something or someone, and through the attitude we take toward unavoidable suffering. The book is short but profoundly impactful, offering wisdom and hope to readers facing their own struggles. It has become a classic in existential psychology and self-help literature.'),

-- CLASSICS (6 books)
('The Great Gatsby', 'F. Scott Fitzgerald', 'Classics', 'The quintessential American novel of the Jazz Age. Jay Gatsby''s obsessive love and the decadence and despair of 1920s society.', 1925, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8265543-M.jpg', 'Nick Carraway moves to West Egg, Long Island, in the summer of 1922 and rents a small house next to the mysterious millionaire Jay Gatsby. Nick''s cousin Daisy and her husband Tom Buchanan live across the bay in East Egg, an area of established wealth. Nick is drawn into the glamorous world of Gatsby''s extravagant parties, where the wealthy dance, drink, and indulge during Prohibition. Nick discovers that Gatsby is obsessed with Daisy and throws his lavish parties hoping to attract her attention. Gatsby once had a relationship with Daisy before he was wealthy, and his goal is to rekindle that romance and marry her. Nick facilitates a reunion between Gatsby and Daisy, but their affair has tragic consequences. Tom becomes jealous, and events spiral toward destruction. Fitzgerald captures the excess and underlying emptiness of the Jazz Age, exploring themes of wealth, love, idealism, and the American Dream. The novel is beautifully written, with rich symbolism and complex characters. Gatsby is a tragic figure—a man whose dreams are noble but ultimately doomed. The book remains relevant for its critique of materialism and its exploration of human desire.'),

('Moby Dick', 'Herman Melville', 'Classics', 'An epic adventure about Captain Ahab''s obsessive quest to hunt down Moby Dick, the white whale that destroyed his ship and took his leg.', 1851, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8268341-M.jpg', 'Ishmael is a sailor who signs aboard the whaling ship Pequod as a crew member. The ship is commanded by Captain Ahab, a man obsessed with hunting Moby Dick, a legendary white whale that had destroyed Ahab''s previous ship, the Essex, and severed Ahab''s leg. Ahab''s obsession drives him to pursue the whale across the oceans, heedless of the danger to his crew. Through Ishmael''s narration, we learn about whaling, the diversity of the Pequod''s international crew, and the mounting tensions as the ship approaches the white whale. The novel blends adventure, philosophy, natural history, and existential meditation. Melville explores themes of obsession, humanity''s relationship with nature, fate versus free will, and the consequences of pride and revenge. The climactic hunt for Moby Dick is harrowing and tragic. The novel is notable for its unconventional structure, digressive chapters on whale anatomy and whaling techniques, and its rich symbolism. While challenging to modern readers due to its length and archaic language, Moby Dick is considered one of the great American novels and a masterpiece of world literature.'),

('Jane Eyre', 'Charlotte Brontë', 'Classics', 'A Gothic romance about a young orphan who becomes a governess and falls in love with the mysterious master of Thornfield Hall.', 1847, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8289543-M.jpg', 'Jane Eyre is an orphan raised by her uncaring aunt. After attending a harsh charity school, she becomes a teacher and then accepts a position as governess to the ward of Edward Rochester. As Jane cares for Rochester''s young ward, Adèle, she develops deep feelings for the brooding master of Thornfield Hall. Rochester is secretive about his past, and strange events occur in the manor—mysterious laughter and fires. Their relationship deepens despite the class differences between them. On their wedding day, a shocking revelation threatens to destroy their happiness. Jane must choose between societal expectations and her heart''s desires. The novel is notable for its strong, independent female protagonist who refuses to be subservient or to sacrifice her principles for love. Jane is intelligent, principled, and takes control of her own destiny. The Gothic atmosphere, the passionate romance, and Jane''s character development make this a compelling story. Themes of independence, morality, love, and female agency run throughout the novel.'),

('Wuthering Heights', 'Emily Brontë', 'Classics', 'A dark, passionate tale of love and revenge on the Yorkshire moors. Heathcliff and Catherine''s love is destructive and spans generations.', 1847, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8294212-M.jpg', 'The story begins when Mr. Lockwood rents Thrushcross Grange and learns the history of the moor from a housekeeper named Nelly Dean. The story is set on the Yorkshire moors and involves two neighboring estates and the interconnected families who inhabit them. Heathcliff, a dark, brooding outsider, arrives at Wuthering Heights as a child and is raised alongside Catherine Earnshaw, with whom he shares a wild, passionate bond. Their love is intense but complicated by social class—Heathcliff is poor while Catherine comes from a wealthy family. When Catherine chooses to marry the respectable Edgar Linton instead of Heathcliff, Heathcliff is devastated and vengeful. He sets out to punish Catherine and her family, creating a cycle of abuse and revenge that spans generations. The novel is dark and violent, with morally ambiguous characters and tragic consequences. Brontë creates an atmosphere of wildness and passion that matches the stark Yorkshire landscape. The novel explores themes of love, revenge, social class, and the destructive power of passion. It remains a powerful and disturbing novel that challenges readers with its dark vision.'),

('Pride and Prejudice', 'Jane Austen', 'Classics', 'A classic romance featuring Elizabeth Bennet and Mr. Darcy in Regency England. A witty examination of marriage, class, and misunderstandings.', 1813, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8235688-M.jpg', 'Elizabeth Bennet is a spirited young woman in Regency-era England, living in a society where a woman''s prospects depend entirely on marriage. When the wealthy Mr. Darcy arrives in their neighborhood, Elizabeth immediately dislikes him, finding him proud and cold. Through a series of events involving her sister Jane, her friend Charlotte, and the deceitful Mr. Wickham, Elizabeth discovers that she has misjudged Darcy. As she uncovers the truth about Wickham and witnesses Darcy''s true character, her feelings change. Darcy, in turn, must overcome his class prejudices to recognize Elizabeth''s worth despite her lower social standing. Their journey from mutual dislike to genuine love is one of literature''s greatest romances. Austen''s wit, sharp social commentary, and well-developed characters make the novel engaging and relevant even today. The novel explores themes of personal growth, seeing beyond appearances, and the importance of marrying for love rather than convenience. Elizabeth is one of literature''s most beloved heroines for her intelligence, independence, and refusal to compromise her principles.'),

('The Odyssey', 'Homer', 'Classics', 'An ancient Greek epic poem about Odysseus''s ten-year journey home after the Trojan War. A tale of adventure, monsters, and the hero''s struggle to return home.', 750, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8241234-M.jpg', 'The Odyssey follows Odysseus, king of Ithaca, as he struggles to return home after the Trojan War. Instead of the expected direct voyage, Odysseus encounters numerous obstacles and supernatural challenges that delay his return for ten years. He faces the Cyclops Polyphemus, the witch Circe, the deadly Sirens, and the wrath of Poseidon. Throughout his journey, Odysseus demonstrates cunning, bravery, and determination, though he also makes mistakes and suffers the consequences. Meanwhile, his wife Penelope waits faithfully, fending off suitors who believe her husband is dead and wish to marry her and claim his kingdom. Their son Telemachus grows up without his father and embarks on his own journey to learn of his father''s fate. The epic is told through an intricate narrative structure that moves between Odysseus''s journey and events in Ithaca. Homer''s Odyssey is foundational to Western literature, exploring themes of heroism, loyalty, perseverance, and the struggle between fate and human agency. The poem has influenced countless works and remains a powerful story of adventure and homecoming.'),

-- NON-FICTION (5 books)
('Educated', 'Tara Westover', 'Non-Fiction', 'A memoir about growing up in a survivalist family with no formal education. Tara''s journey from isolation to intellectual awakening and education.', 2018, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8418923-M.jpg', 'Tara Westover was raised in a survivalist family in rural Idaho by parents who believed the government was a threat and the end times were coming. She had no contact with the outside world, no formal education, and no medical care. Her father controlled every aspect of her life, and her mother practiced herbal medicine despite lacking any medical training. Tara''s childhood was marked by neglect, abuse, and isolation. Against her family''s wishes, at seventeen, Tara teaches herself enough mathematics and grammar to take college entrance exams and is accepted to Brigham Young University. Her journey to higher education is transformative, opening her mind to new possibilities and perspectives. However, it also alienates her from her family, who view her education as a betrayal. The memoir chronicles Tara''s struggle to build a life independent from her family while grappling with the trauma of her upbringing and her conflicted feelings about her parents. Westover''s powerful narrative demonstrates the transformative power of education and the courage required to break free from damaging family systems. The book resonates with readers for its exploration of identity, family trauma, and personal growth.'),

('Sapiens', 'Yuval Noah Harari', 'Non-Fiction', 'A history of humankind from the Stone Age to the modern era. How did humans come to dominate the world and what does the future hold.', 2011, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8404802-M.jpg', 'Yuval Noah Harari traces the history of humanity from the emergence of Homo sapiens approximately 70,000 years ago to the present day. The book is divided into four main sections: the Cognitive Revolution, the Agricultural Revolution, the unification of humankind, and the Scientific Revolution. Harari argues that what set Homo sapiens apart from other human species was our ability to create and believe in shared myths and fictions—money, nations, religions, and human rights are all fictions that allow large numbers of people to cooperate. Through several revolutions, humans created complex societies and accumulated knowledge, eventually dominating the planet. Harari explores how these developments shaped human society and contemplates humanity''s future in a world of artificial intelligence and biotechnology. While critics argue that Harari oversimplifies complex historical processes, the book is thought-provoking and influential for its sweeping perspective and ability to inspire readers to think about the bigger picture.'),

('Atomic Habits', 'James Clear', 'Self-Help', 'Practical strategies for building better habits and breaking bad ones. Small changes, remarkable results. A guide to improvement through incremental progress.', 2018, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8418542-M.jpg', 'Atomic Habits provides a comprehensive framework for understanding how habits work and how to change them. James Clear explains that small changes compound into remarkable results over time. The book outlines key principles for habit formation: making habits obvious, attractive, easy, and satisfying. Clear provides practical techniques such as habit stacking, environmental design, and implementation intentions that readers can immediately apply. The book is filled with engaging stories and examples from athletes and entrepreneurs who have used these principles to transform their lives. Atomic Habits emphasizes that the goal is not to be the best but to be better than you were yesterday. The systems-based approach, where small daily improvements compound into significant changes, has resonated with millions of readers. The book combines scientific research with practical, actionable advice, making it both informative and useful.'),

('Braiding Sweetgrass', 'Robin Wall Kimmerer', 'Non-Fiction', 'Essays on plant wisdom, indigenous knowledge, and our relationship with nature. A beautiful exploration of gratitude and reciprocity with the natural world.', 2013, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8409812-M.jpg', 'Robin Wall Kimmerer is a botanist and member of the Citizen Potawatomi Nation who shares her knowledge of plants and her reflections on indigenous wisdom and our relationship with nature. The essays in Braiding Sweetgrass blend scientific knowledge with indigenous philosophy and personal reflection. Kimmerer explores the idea that plants and nature are not just resources to be exploited but teachers and gifts that deserve gratitude and reciprocity. She discusses how indigenous cultures view their relationship with nature as one of mutual responsibility and care. Kimmerer advocates for a shift in how we view and interact with the natural world—from a perspective of dominance to one of partnership and gratitude. The essays cover topics ranging from strawberries and raspberries to wetlands and cedar, each serving as a lens through which to examine larger themes of sustainability, interconnectedness, and respect for nature. The book is beautifully written, lyrical, and deeply thoughtful. It resonates with readers concerned about environmental sustainability and those seeking a more harmonious relationship with nature. Kimmerer''s voice is gentle, wise, and inspiring, making complex ideas about ecology and indigenous wisdom accessible and compelling.'),

('The Selfish Gene', 'Richard Dawkins', 'Non-Fiction', 'A revolutionary look at evolution from the gene''s perspective. How genes, not organisms, are the primary units of evolution and behavior.', 1976, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8362854-M.jpg', 'Richard Dawkins proposes that genes, rather than organisms or species, are the fundamental units of selection in evolution. From this perspective, organisms are ''vehicles'' for genes, which act to maximize their own replication. This gene-centered view of evolution challenges traditional thinking and has profound implications for understanding behavior, including apparent altruism and cooperation. Dawkins introduces the concept of the meme, a unit of cultural transmission analogous to a gene. Memes replicate through imitation and cultural transmission, and they evolve in ways similar to genetic evolution. The book is provocative and has sparked significant debate in evolutionary biology and philosophy. While many of Dawkins'' ideas have been challenged or refined, the gene-centered perspective remains influential in evolutionary biology. The book is readable and accessible despite dealing with complex scientific concepts. Dawkins'' prose is clear and often witty, making the book engaging even for readers without scientific backgrounds. The Selfish Gene has been instrumental in shaping modern evolutionary thought and continues to influence discussions about genes, behavior, and evolution.'),

